defaultIt is evident that positive changes have taken place in attitudes towards, and opportunities available, to women pursuing STEM careers. However prejudices remain and the ‘glass ceiling’ is perceived to still exist. Much of the problem still relates to the 
defaultstereotyping of females at a young age, the lack of encouragement to study STEM subjects and the subsequent experience of working as a female in a male dominated field. For those with families the main obstacles are the compromise that has to be made when 
defaulttwo individuals wish to pursue professional careers, the need for flexibility around childcare responsibilities and the cost of childcare. These could be addressed by the provision of affordable, conveniently placed childcare and flexible hour contracts. I
defaultn all cases there is a strong need for transparency within promotion procedures and encouragement 
defaultand support to enable
default females
default to
default climb the career ladder. The introduction of a mentoring scheme could help address this issue.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe general consensus is that high achieving women often get overlooked for promotion. An observation is that women are less outwardly ambitious and less good at self-p
defaultromotion than their male equivalents.  Often females will ‘’wait to be asked’’ as opposed to putting themselves forward in the belief that if they keep their heads down and do a 
defaultgood 
defaultjob, their ability will be noticed and promotion will follow. This can be
default interpreted wrongly as a lack of ambition or personal awareness of potential.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe evidence is that 
defaultvisibility
default within the workplace 
defaultcan 
defaultinfluence 
defaultwhether 
defaultone is 
defaultchosen for promotion
default. 
defaultOn this point, although technically the opportunities are equally open t
defaulto men and women, and there are some very good women in senior roles, there is still a critical mass of managers who sub-consciously recruit those like themselves, which results in a series of management clones.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultIf the manager is male, and works in a parti
defaultcular way or style, he will tend to promote those with a similar style
default that he recognises
default, rather than accepting that it would be possible do the job equally well with a different style. There is also the feeling of exclusion from
default certain areas within the 
defaultworkplace, eg
default the friendships 
defaultbetween male colleagues 
defaultand the accompanying bonhomie which can inhibit promotion opportunities if the 
defaultfemale member of staff 
defaultis not seen as ‘’one of the boys’’.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultWomen can be more focussed 
defaultthan men 
defaulton achieving a balance between their personal life and career and as a consequence 
defaultare 
defaultmore often in a position of compromising
default one or both
default. 
defaultThe further up the ladder one rises the more “out of hours” socialising/networking is required. Women are poor at t
defaulthis 
defaultand frequently have primary responsibility for children or elderly relatives - women prioritise these domestic responsibilities rather than networking
default&#xa0;
defaultIt needs to be recognised that it is extremely difficult for two professionals to develop their care
defaulters equit
defaultably (i.e husband and wife) as 
defaultboth cannot necessarily relocate to take on new jobs/promotions. As the role of the female can often be seen as that of the main carer in a family situation, the female 
defaultwill be the one to compromise on
default promotion oppo
defaultrtunities.
